<h3>Bad editorial practices <em>Praxis Filosófica</em> journal</h3>
<p><strong>Bad editorial practices</strong></p>
<p>The ethical regulation of the <em>Praxis Filosófica</em> journal constitutes a fundamental instrument insofar as it guides the authors, evaluators and the editor; However, it is also important to mention practices considered undesirable in the editorial process.</p>
<p><strong>Editors and evaluators</strong></p>
<p>They are considered as bad editorial practices, mainly:</p>
<ul>
<li class="show">Failure to comply with the confidentiality agreement is considered a bad editorial practice.</li>
<li class="show">The use of confidential material not published by the evaluators or editors for personal benefit without recognizing the Intellectual Property Rights.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Authors</strong></p>
<p>The following actions are considered as bad ethical practices by the authors:</p>
<ul>
<li class="show">The falsification of documents presented to the magazine.</li>
<li class="show">The sending of the document to two magazines or media outlets at the same time. The author must comply with an exclusivity agreement with <em>Praxis Filosófica</em>.</li>
<li class="show">The presentation of a document that has already been published in another means of dissemination, whether printed or electronic, including pages such as Scrib or Academia.edu. The authors must comply with an exclusivity agreement certifying that the document is unpublished.</li>
<li class="show">Plagiarism and self-plagiarism is considered a bad practice; in addition, it can be penalized by the Law of Copyright and Intellectual Property.</li>
